cs.CL, cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.DL, cs.CY

This paper is about creating a standardized corpus of Project Gutenberg for statistical analysis of natural language and quantitative linguistics. The paper discusses the potential of the corpus for investigating language variability across time, subjects, and authors. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language) which deals with natural language processing and computational linguistics. The paper also mentions information retrieval, which falls under cs.IR (Information Retrieval). The use of annotated metadata and pre-processing strategies suggests that the paper may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DL (Deep Learning). Finally, the paper's focus on creating a new scientific resource for corpus linguistics suggests that it may also belong to cs.CY (Computers and Society).
